			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>VML* – A Family of Languages for Variability Management in Software Product Lines</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/SteffenZschaler.html">Steffen Zschaler</a>, <a href="../profile/PabloSánchez.html">Pablo Sánchez</a>, <a href="../profile/JõaoSantos.html">Jõao Santos</a>, <a href="../profile/MauricioAlférez.html">Mauricio Alférez</a>, <a href="../profile/AwaisRashid.html">Awais Rashid</a>, <a href="../profile/LidiaFuentes.html">Lidia Fuentes</a>, <a href="../profile/AnaMoreira.html">Ana Moreira</a>, <a href="../profile/JoãoAraújo.html">João Araújo</a>, <a href="../profile/UiráKulesza.html">Uirá Kulesza</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_7">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_7</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2c.html"><span class="tagM">T2C: Variability</span></a><ul><li> The paper proposes a family of languages dedicated to variability management in product lines.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> It introduces DSLs (a family thereof) for expressing variability concepts.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It is about designing the constructs and structure of the VML* language family.
</li></ul></li></ul>
